Prevalence of Diagnosed Diabetes by Age, United States, 1980–2005

From 1980 through 2005, the prevalence of diagnosed diabetes increased in all age groups. In general, throughout the time period, people aged 65-74 years had the highest prevalence, followed by people aged 75 or older, people aged 45-64 years, and people less than 45 years of age. In 2005, the prevalence of diagnosed diabetes among people aged 65-74 (18.5%) was about 12 times that of people less than 45 years of age (1.4%).
